      <text>
        The attack starts subtly. Bioluminescent flashes come from multiple directions—hostile plants signaling each other, coordinating; they've learned from yesterday.

        Florence calls, "Positions!" Not commanding—reminding.

        Everyone is already moving. Velvet's three barrier layers shimmer faintly in the facility's damaged lighting. Remedy positions near the gaps between layers one and two—chemical traps ready. Runner dives underground to monitor hostile root movement. Holloway stays close to me and Scout in the central core.

        The first assault hits the eastern wall—exactly as predicted. Hostile roots punch through the weakened structure, aggressive and coordinated. They hit Velvet's first barrier layer and start tearing through it. The barrier holds briefly, then fails—but that's expected. It's designed to fail.

        The hostile roots push through the gap into empty space—and hit Remedy's chemical trap. Aggressive compounds flood the gap—roots shrivel and withdraw, withering from chemical assault.

        Remedy reports, satisfied, "Eastern approach neutralized."

        Florence warns, "They're adapting—watch for—"

        Northern assault. Hostile plants strike from the direction they avoided yesterday, assuming we're undefended there. But we are. Velvet's barriers hold. Runner attacks from underneath, severing hostile roots before they can establish position. The northern assault stalls.

        Florence analyzes, "They're probing—testing each direction to find our weaknesses."

        I ask nervously, "Do we have weaknesses?" Scout is pressed against me, bouncing, alert.

        Florence says, "Every defense has weaknesses—the question is whether they find them before—"

        ¶

        The whole facility shudders as a massive root surge rises from below.

        Holloway shouts, "Runner, report!"

        Runner replies, strained, "They're hitting the false weak point—northwest, exactly where we wanted. They found it." 

        Florence asks, "Is the trap working?"

        Runner surfaces briefly—vines torn and leaking—and says, strained, "They're committing forces. Lots of them. It's... working too well."

        I say, "What does 'too well' mean?"

        Runner reports, "They're throwing everything at the northwest false weakness—so many hostiles that the trap might not hold."

        Florence calls, "Remedy, can you reinforce northwest?"

        Remedy answers, "I'm positioned at eastern and northern gaps. Can't reach northwest without abandoning these positions."

        Florence calculates quickly, "Velvet, redirect growth to northwest—shore up the—"

        Velvet interrupts, "If I pull from the southern barrier, the south becomes vulnerable."

        Exactly on cue, the southern assault begins—hostile plants striking from a fourth direction simultaneously.

        We're surrounded again, but this time with better defenses. The question is whether better is enough.

        Florence says firmly, "Adapt—everyone use judgment. I can't predict every move—you're all tactical assets, act like it."

        That's... actually empowering. Scary, but empowering.
      </text>
