        Florence says, "Positions."
        It's not a command—coordinating.

        Florence continues, "Velvet and Runner, combine growth downward at Runner's identified command node location—Remedy, deploy compounds: accelerants for our plants, withering for hostiles—Holloway, be ready to protect Kira if anything goes wrong—everyone else, prepare to attack whatever surfaces."

        Everyone moves—Velvet and Runner position together, growth intertwining. It's bizarre and beautiful: two plants merging their efforts, growing as one organism downward into the earth.

        Remedy floods the area with chemicals, surrounding Velvet and Runner with growth accelerants while pouring withering compounds into the ground above the command node location.

        Underground, chaos must be forming—hostile command node trapped between aggressive growth from above and toxic chemicals from all sides.

        The ground shakes—something is moving underground, something big.

        Runner reports, "It's working—command node is shifting upward—trying to escape."

        Velvet says, "Keep pressure!" Their combined growth accelerates.

        More shaking, louder—the entire facility structure groans.

        ¶

        Then the floor erupts.

        Massive hostile plant network surfaces: an enormous root system with bioluminescent command nodes, coordinating tendrils spreading everywhere. It's the central intelligence controlling the whole attack—and it's right in the middle of our defensive perimeter.

        Florence shouts, "*NOW!*"

        Everyone attacks.

        Velvet's barriers grow inward, constricting the hostile command node—Runner's vines sever connection points—Remedy floods it with every aggressive compound left—Holloway positions fruiting bodies to block escape routes.

        Scout and I watch from our protected corner, stunned by the coordinated assault: every plant using its unique ability at once, working together.

        The hostile command node writhes and tries to withdraw, but it's surrounded—outnumbered and outmaneuvered by cooperative strategy it cannot counter.

        Velvet constricts—Runner severs—Remedy dissolves—Holloway blocks.

        The command node collapses.

        ¶

        Instantly, all the hostile assault forces stop coordinating. The bioluminescent signals cut off—without central intelligence directing them, the attacking plants lose cohesion.

        They withdraw—not an organized retreat, just individual plants pulling back, recognizing the attack failed.

        We won.

        The facility falls silent except for everyone's exhausted breathing—or whatever the plant equivalent of exhausted breathing is.

        I ask quietly, "Is it over?"

        Florence surveys the battlefield—hostile plants retreating on all sides, the command node destroyed in the center of our perimeter. Our defenses are damaged but holding.

        Florence confirms, "It's over— they can't coordinate without their command structure. They'll regroup eventually, but not today."

        Scout bounces, relieved—an exhausted, relieved bounce.
      </text>
